    category: "general",
    content: `<h2>Post-Surgical Recovery Tips: A Patient's Complete Guide</h2>
<p>A successful surgical outcome depends not only on the skill of your surgeon but also on how well you manage your recovery. Proper post-operative care can significantly influence healing, reduce complications, and ensure the best possible results. Dr. Prasanna Somvanshi, a leading plastic surgeon in Mumbai, provides comprehensive post-operative instructions to every patient, but this guide offers a general overview of what to expect and how to optimise your recovery after plastic surgery.</p>

<h2>General Recovery Timeline</h2>
<p>Every procedure has its own recovery timeline, but there are common phases that most patients experience:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Days 1 to 3 (Acute Phase):</strong> This is the period of maximum swelling, discomfort, and potential bruising. Pain medication prescribed by Dr. Somvanshi should be taken as directed. Rest is essential during this phase</li>
<li><strong>Days 4 to 7 (Early Recovery):</strong> Swelling begins to subside, and most patients start feeling significantly better. Suture removal or first follow-up visits typically occur during this period</li>
<li><strong>Weeks 2 to 4 (Progressive Recovery):</strong> Most patients can return to desk jobs and light daily activities. Swelling continues to decrease, and bruising fades</li>
<li><strong>Months 1 to 3 (Maturation Phase):</strong> Surgical sites continue to heal internally. Scars begin to mature and may appear red or raised before gradually fading</li>
<li><strong>Months 3 to 12 (Final Healing):</strong> Scars continue to soften and lighten. Final surgical results become fully apparent during this period</li>
</ul>

<h2>Wound Care Essentials</h2>
<p>Proper wound care is one of the most important aspects of recovery. Dr. Prasanna Somvanshi provides specific wound care instructions tailored to each procedure, but here are general guidelines:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Keep the wound clean and dry:</strong> Follow your surgeon's instructions regarding when you can shower or bathe. Avoid submerging surgical sites in water (bathtubs, swimming pools) until cleared by your doctor</li>
<li><strong>Change dressings as instructed:</strong> Use sterile materials and clean hands when changing dressings. If you are unsure about how to perform a dressing change, ask the nursing team to demonstrate before discharge</li>
<li><strong>Apply prescribed ointments:</strong> Antibiotic ointments or silicone-based scar gels should be applied as directed. Do not use over-the-counter creams or home remedies on surgical wounds without consulting your surgeon</li>
<li><strong>Protect wounds from sun exposure:</strong> UV radiation can darken healing scars permanently. Use sunscreen with SPF 50 or cover the area with clothing or tape when outdoors</li>
</ul>

<h2>Nutrition for Optimal Healing</h2>
<p>What you eat after surgery directly affects your body's ability to heal. Dr. Somvanshi recommends the following dietary guidelines:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Increase protein intake:</strong> Protein is the building block of tissue repair. Include eggs, dal, paneer, chicken, fish, and legumes in your diet. Aim for at least 1.2 to 1.5 grams of protein per kilogram of body weight daily</li>
<li><strong>Stay hydrated:</strong> Drink at least 8 to 10 glasses of water daily. Adequate hydration supports circulation and helps your body flush out anaesthetic agents and metabolic waste</li>
<li><strong>Eat fruits and vegetables:</strong> Vitamins A and C are particularly important for wound healing. Include citrus fruits, papaya, guava, spinach, and carrots in your meals</li>
<li><strong>Include zinc-rich foods:</strong> Zinc plays a critical role in immune function and cell division. Nuts, seeds, whole grains, and dairy products are good sources</li>
<li><strong>Avoid processed foods and excess sugar:</strong> These can promote inflammation and impair healing</li>
<li><strong>Limit salt intake:</strong> Excess sodium can worsen post-operative swelling</li>
</ul>

<h2>Activity Restrictions</h2>
<p>Resuming activities too quickly is one of the most common mistakes patients make after surgery. Follow these general guidelines, though your specific restrictions will be outlined by Dr. Prasanna Somvanshi based on your procedure:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Avoid strenuous exercise</strong> for at least 4 to 6 weeks after surgery. This includes gym workouts, running, heavy lifting, and contact sports</li>
<li><strong>Walking is encouraged</strong> from the first day after surgery. Gentle walking promotes blood circulation and reduces the risk of blood clots</li>
<li><strong>Avoid bending and straining</strong> for the first two weeks, as this can increase swelling and risk of bleeding</li>
<li><strong>Do not drive</strong> until you are off pain medication and can perform an emergency stop without pain</li>
<li><strong>Avoid smoking and alcohol</strong> for at least 4 weeks before and after surgery. Smoking impairs blood flow and significantly increases the risk of wound complications</li>
</ul>

<h2>Follow-Up Visits</h2>
<p>Dr. Somvanshi schedules regular follow-up visits at his affiliated hospitals including NH SRCC, SevenHills, Surya Hospital, HN Reliance, MRR Hospital, and Sushrusha Hospital. These visits are essential for monitoring healing, removing sutures, and addressing any concerns. Do not skip follow-up appointments even if you feel well, as some complications can develop without obvious symptoms.</p>

<h2>Warning Signs: When to Contact Your Surgeon Immediately</h2>
<p>While most recoveries proceed smoothly, you should contact Dr. Somvanshi's team immediately if you experience any of the following:</p>
<ul>
<li>Fever above 101 degrees Fahrenheit (38.3 degrees Celsius)</li>
<li>Increasing redness, warmth, or swelling around the wound</li>
<li>Foul-smelling or cloudy discharge from the wound</li>
<li>Sudden increase in pain not relieved by prescribed medication</li>
<li>Excessive bleeding or blood-soaked dressings</li>
<li>Shortness of breath, chest pain, or calf swelling (which may indicate a blood clot)</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Your recovery is a partnership between you and your surgical team.</strong> By following Dr. Prasanna Somvanshi's post-operative instructions carefully, maintaining good nutrition, and attending all follow-up visits, you give yourself the best chance of an excellent result. If you have any questions during your recovery, do not hesitate to contact our clinic. We are here to support you every step of the way.</p>`,
